# Managed by Ansible. http-scoped rate limiting for the go-ledger vhost
# (Task 5.2, audit A2.5/A6.4): a per-IP request flood at the edge, ahead of
# anything the application itself can do about it.
#
# limit_req_zone MUST be declared in the http block; this role only manages
# one vhost's server block (see templates/go.sohag.pro.conf.j2), not the
# shared nginx.conf http block itself (the box also serves an unrelated
# portfolio site this role does not own). Debian/Ubuntu's stock nginx.conf
# includes /etc/nginx/conf.d/*.conf from inside its http block, so dropping
# the zone declaration here reaches http scope without this role ever
# touching nginx.conf or any other site's config.
#
# Zone size: 10m holds roughly 160k tracked IPs ($binary_remote_addr is 4 or
# 16 bytes, plus per-entry bookkeeping; nginx docs put roughly 16000 IPs per
# megabyte for the smaller IPv4 case), far more than this single box will
# ever see distinct source IPs within a request window.
#
# Rate: 20r/s per IP is generous for a legitimate integration (the demo key's
# own application-level limit is 60 requests per MINUTE, an order of
# magnitude tighter) while still giving the edge a hard backstop against a
# single source hammering the box faster than any per-key limit downstream
# could even get evaluated. Tune the rate here and the burst per location in
# go.sohag.pro.conf.j2; both are deliberately named "go_ledger_api" so they
# are easy to find together.
limit_req_zone $binary_remote_addr zone=go_ledger_api:10m rate=20r/s;
